Here is a list of common HTML tags with short descriptions of their uses:

Basic Structure Tags:
<!DOCTYPE html>: Declares the document type and version of HTML.
<html>: The root element that contains all other HTML elements.
<head>: Contains metadata, links to scripts, and stylesheets.
<title>: Sets the title of the document, shown in the browser tab.
<body>: Contains the visible content of the webpage.


Text and Formatting Tags:
<h1> to <h6>: Headings, with <h1> being the most important and <h6> the least.
<p>: Defines a paragraph of text.
<b>: Makes text bold without emphasis.
<strong>: Adds strong emphasis, usually bold.
<i>: Italicizes text without emphasis.
<em>: Adds emphasized text, usually italic.
<u>: Underlines text.
<br>: Inserts a line break.
<hr>: Creates a horizontal rule, often used to separate content.
<blockquote>: Used for long quotations.
<mark>: Highlights or marks text.
<small>: Reduces the font size of the text.
<sup>: Creates superscript text (e.g., for footnotes).
<sub>: Creates subscript text (e.g., for chemical formulas).
<pre>: Displays preformatted text with spaces and line breaks intact.


Links and Media Tags:
<a>: Defines a hyperlink to link one page to another.
<img>: Embeds an image.
<audio>: Embeds audio content.
<video>: Embeds video content.
<source>: Specifies multiple media sources for <video> and <audio> elements.
<iframe>: Embeds another HTML page inside the current one.
<embed>: Embeds external content (such as PDFs or media players).


List Tags:
<ul>: Defines an unordered (bulleted) list.
<ol>: Defines an ordered (numbered) list.
<li>: Defines a list item in an ordered or unordered list.
<dl>: Defines a description list.
<dt>: Defines a term in a description list.
<dd>: Defines a description or value in a description list.


Table Tags:
<table>: Defines a table.
<tr>: Defines a row in a table.
<td>: Defines a cell in a table row.
<th>: Defines a header cell in a table.
<thead>: Groups the header content in a table.
<tbody>: Groups the body content in a table.
<tfoot>: Groups the footer content in a table.
<caption>: Adds a caption to a table.


Form Tags:
<form>: Defines a form for user input.
<input>: Defines an input field where users can enter data.
<button>: Defines a clickable button.
<select>: Defines a dropdown list.
<option>: Defines an option within a dropdown list.
<textarea>: Defines a multiline text input field.
<label>: Associates a label with a form control.
<fieldset>: Groups related elements in a form.
<legend>: Defines a caption for the <fieldset> element.


Semantic and Layout Tags:
<div>: A generic container for grouping content, mainly used for layout purposes.
<span>: A generic inline container for text or other inline elements.
<header>: Defines the header of a section or page.
<footer>: Defines the footer of a section or page.
<main>: Specifies the main content of the document.
<section>: Defines a section in the document.
<article>: Defines an independent, self-contained content piece.
<aside>: Defines content that is tangentially related to the main content.
<nav>: Defines a navigation block for links.


Interactive Tags:
<details>: Creates a widget that the user can open or close.
<summary>: Defines a summary for the <details> element.
<dialog>: Defines a dialog box or window.
<progress>: Displays progress of a task.
<meter>: Displays a scalar measurement within a known range.
Meta and Script Tags:


<meta>: Defines metadata about an HTML document.
<link>: Links an external resource (like stylesheets).
<style>: Embeds CSS styles in the document.
<script>: Embeds or links to JavaScript code.


Document Structure Tags:
<section>: Represents a standalone section that can exist independently from the rest of the document.
<article>: Used for independent, self-contained content.
<aside>: For content indirectly related to the main content.

These tags are the building blocks of any HTML document, and understanding them helps in creating structured, accessible, and well-formatted web pages.
